Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

The child component has overwriten the parent component's selector and template  when child component inherit a parent component, as shown in the following code.  'draggable' is parent component and 'app-content' is child component.

If I  choose to use 'ng-content' in the template of 'DraggableComponent', and move the temple code of child component to solve the problem  , I have to modify the child component and parent component. Can the angular framework support parent component's selector and template remaining valid in child template.

```ts
// parent component
@Component({
  selector: 'draggable',
  template: '<p>{{ message }}</p>'
})
export class DraggableComponent {
  message = 'Hello from parent';
  dragStart(evt: any, currentCursorType: string = 'ew') {
  }

  dragEnd(evt: any) {
  }

  ewResize(evt: any) {
  }
}
```

```ts
// child component
@Component({
  selector: 'app-content',
  template: `
    <p>{{ message }} (from child template)</p>
    <!--  DraggableComponent -->
    <draggable></draggable>
  `
})
export class ContentComponent extends DraggableComponent {
  // 
}
```


### Proposed solution

I suggest adding a parameter in the parent or child "@Component" that says whether to keep the parent selector and parent template.

In this example, if adding in child "@Component", 

```ts
// parent component
@Component({
  selector: 'draggable',
  template: '<p>{{ message }}</p>'
})
export class DraggableComponent {
  message = 'Hello from parent';
  dragStart(evt: any, currentCursorType: string = 'ew') {
  }

  dragEnd(evt: any) {
  }

  ewResize(evt: any) {
  }
}
```

```ts
// child component
@Component({
  selector: 'app-content',
  template: `
    <p>{{ message }} (from child template)</p>
    <!--  DraggableComponent -->
    <draggable></draggable>
  `,
  keep
})
export class ContentComponent extends DraggableComponent {
  // 
}
```


### Alternatives considered

none

* Define `ResourceSnapshot<T>` as a type union of possible states for a `Resource<T>`.
* Add `Resource.snapshot()` to convert a `Resource` to a signal of its snapshot.
* Add `resourceFromSnapshots` to convert a reactive snapshot back into a `Resource`.

By converting resources from/to `Signal<ResourceSnapshot>`s, full composition of resources is now possible on top of signal composition APIs like `computed` and `linkedSignal`.

For example, a common feature request is to have a `Resource` which retains its value when its reactive source (params) changes. This can now be built as a utility, leveraging `linkedSignal`'s previous value capability:

```ts
function withPreviousValue<T>(input: Resource<T>): Resource<T> {
  const derived = linkedSignal({
    source: input.snapshot,
    computation: (snap, previous) => {
      if (snap.status === 'loading' && previous?.value) {
        // When the input resource enters loading state, we keep the value
        // from its previous state, if any.
        return {status: 'loading', value: previous.value.value};
      }

      // Otherwise we simply forward the state of the input resource.
      return snap;
    },
  });

  return resourceFromSnapshots(derived);
}

// In application code:

userId = input.required<number>();
user = withPreviousValue(httpResource(() => `/user/{this.userId()}`));
// if `userId()` switches, `user.value()` will keep the old value until
// the new one is ready!
```

### Command

new

### Description

The included Angular Prettier config should go into it's own file, instead of being added to the package.json.

**package.json**

```
{
  "prettier": {
    "printWidth": 100,
    "singleQuote": true,
    "overrides": [
      {
        "files": "*.html",
        "options": {
          "parser": "angular"
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

### Describe the solution you'd like

While ".prettierrc" is the most common variant, I recommend using the modern approach "prettier.config.js" - this aligns with other tools like ESLint, Cypress or Playwright and allows comments:

**prettier.config.js**

```
module.exports = {
  bracketSameLine: true, // default: false; true for fewer lines in .html
  printWidth: 120, // default: 80; adjust to your team's preference
  singleQuote: true, // default: false; true for JS community style
  overrides: [
    {
      files: '*.html',
      options: {
        parser: 'angular',
      },
    },
  ],
};
```

Additionally, ".prettierignore" should be added with the minimal content like this:

**.prettierignore**
```
/.angular
/coverage
/dist
/node_modules
```


### Describe alternatives you've considered

If you don't like "bracketSameLine: true" and insist on "printWidth: 100" that's okay, then we would have:

**prettier.config.js**

```
module.exports = {
  printWidth: 100, // default: 80; adjust to your team's preference
  singleQuote: true, // default: false; true for JS community style
  overrides: [
    {
      files: '*.html',
      options: {
        parser: 'angular',
      },
    },
  ],
};
```
